>
>I just went through this myself (put a 78 engine in my 79.)  There
>should be a wire from the + side of the coil (terminal 15) going to 
>terminal
>86c on the relay.  This wire provides power to the relay, and if
>I remember correctly, controls the switching of power to 88b.  There should 
>also
>be a wire from the coil (terminal 15 again) to the fan relay, which
>in turn gets juice from the ignition switch (I'm a little foggy on this
>part as my PO had removed the fan ran the ign wire straight to the coil.)
>
>So, to summarize, turn on the key, test power to terminal 15 of the
>coil (+ side) and if that is good, check power to terminal 86c on the
>double relay.  I'm willing to bet this is where the problem is.
>
>Rob
>
> > I tried following the Bentley book in testing the double
> > relay. The relay seems to have positive in the right place
> > when the key is off. With the key on, it does not seem to
> > energize 88b as it is supposed to. Also, we are supposed to
> > check for presence of ground on 85, but what seems to be
> > labeled 85 doesn't seem to have a pin long enough to check
> > (or I am checking it and it isn't showing ground). This was
> > all working with the old engine, so I don't think the relay
> > is bad. Also we tried another relay that Lou says is "known
> > good" and it didn't work either.
> >
> > I'm thinking that maybe wherever the signal goes into the
> > relay to switch-on 88b is where the fault is, but I don't
> > understand from the wiring diagram where I should be
> > checking. The switched positive from the keyswitch up front
> > must run back somewhere, through someting and eventually to
> > an unknown pin on the double relay. I think I should be
> > working backwards from the where this signal comes into the
> > relay, but I don't see where to check.
> >
> > Any guesses what we didn't hook up right? Any suggestions on
> > any of this in general?
> >
> > Thanks much!
> >
> > Mark
